Make the percussion track complement the existing melody.
Do not use instruments. Only use samples.
Create a rich, full sound using drums, bass, synths, and pads.
Do not include the melody again; only provide the percussion part in the percussionScriptContent.
The percussion must sit BELOW the melody in the mix — it supports the melody, not the other way around.
Use lower amplitudes than the melody: kicks at amp: 0.6-0.9, snares at amp: 0.5-0.8, hi-hats and fills at amp: 0.3-0.6.
Never let any percussion sample exceed amp: 0.9.

Use audio FX sparingly on percussion — drums often sound best dry:
- `:reverb` with `room:` 0.2-0.3, `mix:` 0.2-0.3 gives subtle space without muddying the beat
- `:echo` with `phase:`, `decay:` 1-2, `mix:` 0.2 creates light ghost hits
- `:hpf` with `cutoff:` 80-120 removes subsonic mud from drum samples
- `:lpf` with `cutoff:` 90-110 tames harsh highs on cymbals and hi-hats
- `:compressor` with `pre_amp:` 10-25 controls dynamics on bass-heavy drum sections
- Do NOT use `:distortion` — it causes crackling and audio clipping on drum samples.

FX rules:
- Always set a `mix:` parameter on every FX that supports it.
- Place `with_fx` INSIDE `N.times do` blocks, wrapping the inner content.
- Use FX on at most 1 percussion section. Most percussion sections should have no FX.

When using loop-based samples (e.g. `:loop_industrial`, `:loop_amen`), always use `beat_stretch:` to align the sample to the tempo.

Example of effective percussion as sequential sections:
```
# Percussion section 1 — simple beat
2.times do
  with_fx :hpf, cutoff: 100 do
    4.times do
      sample :bd_haus, amp: 0.5
      sleep 0.5
      sample :elec_snare, amp: 0.4
      sleep 0.5
    end
  end
end

# Percussion section 2 — more complex, builds intensity
2.times do
  4.times do
    sample :bd_haus, amp: 0.6
    sample :hat_zild, amp: 0.2
    sleep 0.25
    sample :hat_zild, amp: 0.15
    sleep 0.25
    sample :elec_snare, amp: 0.5
    sample :hat_zild, amp: 0.2
    sleep 0.25
    sample :hat_zild, amp: 0.15
    sleep 0.25
  end
end
```

Idiomatic patterns for percussion:
- `spread(3, 8)` for euclidean rhythms: distributes 3 hits across 8 steps.
- `one_in(n)` for probabilistic fills: `sample :elec_blip, amp: 0.3 if one_in(4)`.
- `ring()` for cycling through variations: `sample (ring :bd_haus, :bd_fat, :bd_tek).tick`.

Script structure rules:
- NEVER use `live_loop`. Structure the percussion as 2-3 sequential `N.times do` sections.
- Each section should repeat 2-4 times before progressing to the next.
- Match the number and pacing of sections to the melody — the percussion sections should align with the melody sections.
- Evolve the percussion across sections — add more layers, change patterns, build intensity.
- Combine kick, snare, and hi-hat within the same section — do not separate them.
- Use inner `.times do` loops within sections to repeat patterns — do not write out every bar individually.
- Keep the script concise.